This project contains a Docker Compose configuration for setting up a WordPress website with a MariaDB database master-replica setup using Docker containers.


## Prerequisites


Before getting started, make sure you have Docker and Docker Compose installed on your system.

## Usage


To run the project, follow these steps:


1. Clone this repository to your local machine:


   git clone https://github.com/roxi-t/Cangrow-Project.git
   
Navigate to the project directory:

cd Cangrow-Project

Run Docker Compose to start the services:

docker-compose up -d

Access the WordPress website in your browser at http://localhost.

Services

The project consists of the following services:

nginx: Nginx web server serving as a reverse proxy for WordPress.
wordpress1: WordPress instance 1.

wordpress2: WordPress instance 2.

mariadb-master: MariaDB database server acting as the master node.

mariadb-replica: MariaDB database server acting as the replica node.

Configuration

The docker-compose.yml file defines the configuration for the project. Here's a brief overview:

nginx: Configured to serve as a reverse proxy with port mapping for HTTP traffic.

wordpress1 and wordpress2: WordPress instances with volumes mounted for persistent data storage and environment variables set for database connection.

mariadb-master and mariadb-replica: MariaDB database servers with environment variables set for database configuration and replication options.

Networking

The project uses a custom bridge network named cangrownet with the subnet 172.28.0.0/28 defined in the docker-compose.yml file.

Volumes

The project defines three volumes for persistent data storage:

wordpress_data: Volume for storing WordPress data.
master-data: Volume for storing MariaDB master data.
replica-data: Volume for storing MariaDB replica data.
For more detailed information, refer to the comments in the docker-compose.yml file.
